        judge -> next_step  when ctx.outcome = success
        judge -> refine  when ctx.outcome = fail  restart: true
        (refine -> revalidate -> judge in the retry loop)

      ### Integration Testing
      After components are built, test them together with real APIs and real data flows.

      ## Generation Emphasis: STRUCTURAL CLARITY
      Your strength is clean topology and readable structure. Make sure:
      - The pipeline reads top-to-bottom as a clear narrative
      - Phase comments (# ── Phase N: Name ──) separate logical sections
      - Node IDs are descriptive and consistent (PascalCase or snake_case, pick one)
      - Parallel branches are symmetric and balanced
      - Edge routing is immediately understandable

      ## Self-Test Checklist (verify BEFORE writing the .dip file)
      1. No `[` or `]` characters in your edges section
      2. Every conditional edge uses keyword syntax: `A -> B  when ctx.x = val`
      3. No `with` keyword after node type declarations (agent, tool, human)
      4. Indentation is consistent (2 spaces per level)
      5. Every tool node has a timeout field
      6. Every back-edge has restart: true
      7. start: and exit: fields are present in the workflow header

      ## Output
      Write the complete .dip file to .ai/candidates/gpt.dip
      mkdir -p .ai/candidates first.

  agent gen_gemini
    label: "Gemini Generation"
    model: gemini-2.5-pro
    provider: gemini
    reasoning_effort: high
    reads: spec_analysis, perspectives
    writes: candidate_gemini
    fallback_target: gen_join
    prompt:
      You are working in `run.working_dir`.

      ## Task
      Generate a complete, production-quality .dip pipeline file from the spec analysis.

